## Executive Summary
This report reviews research on teaching Year 10 Computer Science students to interpret and use exam command words (e.g. explain, describe, evaluate). We define our group as “Year 10 OCR GCSE Computer Science students who struggled to interpret and respond to command words.” We summarize each provided source (assessing relevance, strengths/limitations, and its support for arguments about command-word literacy, assessment literacy, scaffolding, feedback, etc.). Key findings include: students often conflate command terms, leading to shallow answers
; explicit instruction and modeling of command-word responses can improve understanding
; high-order questioning promotes deeper learning
; and fostering students’ assessment literacy (including confidence and metacognitive skills) is crucial
. We propose research questions aligned to the brief, synthesize findings into themes (e.g. Assessment Literacy, Self-efficacy, Scaffolding/Modeling, Feedback/Reflection, and Knowledge Transfer), and map them to classroom strategies (e.g. teaching command-word definitions, exemplar answers, varied contexts). We also outline how to use available Unit 1–3 assessment data (with limitations) and classroom handouts as evidence, suggest a 4–6 week intervention timeline (via a Mermaid Gantt chart), and identify data to collect (pre/post scores, answer length, confidence surveys). Finally, we list 20–30 recommended sources (peer-reviewed, government, exam-board) and search strategies/databases for further literature.

## Research Questions
To guide the evaluation, we frame the following research questions:

RQ1: What specific difficulties do Year 10 GCSE Computer Science students experience with exam command words (e.g. explain, describe, evaluate)?
RQ2: Which classroom strategies and instructional practices effectively improve students’ command-word comprehension and extended-response writing?
RQ3: How can we measure improvement in student understanding of command words and related exam performance?
Each question ties to the assignment brief by focusing on the defined group (Year 10 students with command-word difficulties in Computer Science) and the goal (critically evaluating how teaching strategies improved their learning).
